Japan, Indonesia, South Korea, Philippines: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-04-25T22:24:11Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-25/japan-indonesia-south-korea-philippines-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Edano will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will sell 2.6 trillion yen ($31.7
billion) of two-year notes today. The ministry will announce a
coupon for the new securities at 10:30 a.m.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.225 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The yen traded at
81.89 per dollar at 7:13 a.m. in  Tokyo .  Indonesia : The government will sell five-, 10- and 15-year
maturity Islamic bonds. The yield on the 8.25 percent note due
July 2021 was 7.83 percent. The rupiah was at 8,613.  Singapore: Industrial production climbed 23.8 percent in
March from a year earlier after rising 4.8 percent the previous
month, according to a Bloomberg survey of economists before
official data today.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.46 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.2345.  South Korea: Consumer confidence rebounded from a 23-month
low and inflation expectations reached the Bank of Korea’s 4
percent target ceiling, adding pressure on the central bank to
raise  interest rates . The sentiment index rose to 100 in April
from 98 in March, ending a four-month losing streak, the central
bank said in an e-mailed statement in  Seoul  today. A reading of
100 indicates the number of pessimists equal that of optimists.  The yield on  South Korea ’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.85 percent. The won was at 1,081.35 per dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will sell a combined 95
billion baht ($3.2 billion) of 28-, 91-, 182- and 364-day bills.  The yield on the 3.125 percent bond due December 2015 was
3.3 percent. The baht was at 29.93 per dollar.  Taiwan: The government will sell NT$40 billion ($1.4
billion) of five-year bonds.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 1.36
percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar was at NT$28.892.  Philippines: The Bureau of the Treasury will sell 9 billion
pesos ($208 million) of 10-year bonds.  The yield on the 7.375 percent note due March 2021 was 6.45
percent. The peso was at 43.193 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in  Singapore  at 
